    {
        "content": "<p>A <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/discrete%20fibration\">[[discrete fibration]]</a> is a functor satisfying a property. However, every discrete fibration over a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> is specified by simpler data: namely a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|E|</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span></span></span></span>, a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p : |E| \\to |B|</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span></span></span></span>, and for each morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>e</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b \\to p(e)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> an element of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|E|</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span></span></span></span> satisfying a unitality and associativity law.</p>\n<p>I would like terminology for this data that differentiates it from a discrete fibration (I am working in a setting where the analogues of these two notions are different enough to warrant different names). However, I've been struggling to find good terminology in the literature.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Mac Lane calls them \"left-<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>-objects\" or \"internal diagrams\".</li>\n<li>Borceux calls them \"internal base-valued functors\".</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I would like terminology that doesn't involve \"internal\", and ideally captures the intuition of a \"lifting\" operation or fibres in some way. Is there any such terminology in the literature already, or does anyone have any suggestions?</p>",
        "id": 514534489,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1745670510
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the context of Lie groupoids, I am aware of some terminology for fibrations with splitting cleavage  described via left actions:</p>\n<p>For example, </p>\n<ul>\n<li>In the context of the left action of a Lie groupoid <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">X</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>⇉</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{X}:=[X_1 \\rightrightarrows X_0]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⇉</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> on a manifold <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span> equipped with an right action of a Lie group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>, they are sometimes called a <em>principal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>-bundle over the Lie groupoid <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">X</span></span></span></span></em> (Definition 2.2 in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0401420\">Chern-Weil map for principal bundles over groupoids</a>).</li>\n<li>\n<p>In the context of tangent bundle over a Lie groupoid they are sometimes called <em>Ehresmann connection on Lie groupoids</em> (as in the section 2.4 of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/0911.2859\">Representations up to homotopy and Bott’s spectral sequence for\nLie groupoids</a>).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>In the context of representation theory of Lie groupoids, they are sometimes called  <em>representations of Lie groupoids</em> (See section 2.1 of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1007.3658\">VB-GROUPOIDS AND REPRESENTATION THEORY OF LIE\nGROUPOIDS</a>).</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>However, it is also possible that I might have misunderstood your question.</p>",
        "id": 514541158,
        "sender_full_name": "Adittya Chaudhuri",
        "timestamp": 1745675532
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What about calling it a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>-graded set?</p>",
        "id": 514545860,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1745678855
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My instinct would be \"left <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>-module\".</p>",
